    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Encroachments! It's a broad term, much wider than just building too close to the street, though that is certainly a big part of it. It refers to any structure, object, or activity that intrudes upon property lines or public easements without proper permission. Think of it like a rogue trash pile left on the sidewalk, or perhaps a small, unauthorized shed built over the property line—the city cares about *any* intrusion.\n\nIllegal encroachments can range from a poorly placed fence that bleeds onto the neighbor's yard, to utility poles or signs placed where they shouldn't be. In residential areas, they often scrutinize things like decks that overhang the property line or even large satellite dishes mounted in ways that violate sightline regulations. It's all about maintaining the established character and safe use of the public space, preventing little acts of property boundary chaos.\n\nThe city is basically looking to make sure your project doesn't look like a disorganized cluster of misplaced belongings, which is what a poorly managed warren of little, greedy goblins might look like. If your grocery's awning juts out too far, that's an encroachment; if you leave a pile of discarded vegetable peelings on",
